Remarks: Stately two-story with distinctive style and character. This is an amazing buy right in the heart of Old Federal Heights. Cared for and loved by the current owner since 1972. A grand entry has a beautiful staircase and elegant millwork. Spacious formal living and dining rooms flow off the entry. A bright sunroom and den is tucked behind elegant French doors. Hardwood floors enhance the formal spaces. A breeze screen porch adjoins the living room. The kitchen is updated with crisp white cabinets and black granite. A gorgeous powder room is on the main. Three lovely upper level bedrooms include a fantastic master suite with fireplace, spa bath and wonderful sitting room. All baths have been nicely redone. The lower level has amazing storage, laundry and a deluxe game room lined in rich oak paneling. A super cool oak bar adjoins the rec room. The yard is a small urban garden style with a crisp new deck, new fence and great patio space. The garage has double door access from the alley behind and the street in front. This is a charmer nestled on one of the greatest streets of Salt Lake. Note the recent roof, updated interiors and custom awnings.

Remarks: Remarkable, renovated Federal Heights brick rambler that reflects quality and exudes an informal elegance. The beauty of the open concept living room and dining room is accentuated by the handsome coffered ceiling, hand scraped solid cherry flooring and series of prairie styled windows. The artistry and craftsmanship of the woodworking is evident in the triple crown mouldings, high baseboards, solid core doors with raised wood paneling, flooring and the window and door trim found throughout the home. The well-equipped gourmet kitchen has a large center island which is ideal for serving, bar seating, storage and lively conversations. The main level master suite has two spacious walk-in-closets and a luxurious bath with a steam shower which is a rare find. From the master bedroom window you can hear the melodic sounds of the water feature outside in the hosta garden. The lower level is partially above grade and has a recreation room, a second kitchen, secondary bedrooms, an optional wine cellar and a private patio with a hot tub. Enjoy entertaining, and relaxing from multiple outdoor venues, such as the spacious backyard trellised patio overlooking the beautifully redesigned backyard gardens that disburse blue and green tones from the evergreens which are complimented with a variety of colorful deciduous trees, scrubs and perennials or in the screened in patio orthe covered front porch. All this, within minutes to the University of Utah, downtown and nearby mountain trails.

Remarks: There's several solid reasons that we love this adorable place in Marmalade. Never mind that some of our favorite COLLECTIVE pals have lived here, but they've also put in the blood, sweat, and tears to make it feel like any cozy/cute/updated/perfect-for-having-the-homies-over casa should feel. Lucky buyers will be reaping the benefits of said work, and there's nothing like moving in and getting comfy without much effort. This one has loads of curb appeal, but the best part is, you're not actually perched right on the curb–a private walk leads to the front door, which is perfectly tucked back for a nice, secluded touch. That front yard? All garden, and all organic (think Oregon berries, pumpkins, peppers to melt your face)...which means more space in that ideally-sized back yard for, say, BBQing/wining/dining (on the brand new deck), raising chickens, and corn holing. Inside is a pleasant surprise, to say the least. A clean layout gives way to one bedroom downstairs and one, goodly loft-style room (with office area) upstairs. And we mustn't forget that little top-window nook; it's screaming for a cozy bunch of pillows to create the perfect reading spot (mind the gap). The current (awesome) owners took it upon themselves to give the kitchen a full-blown facelift, and it was a well-advised effort. Wood on the wall was sourced from a dilapidated cabin in Utah, and the metal backsplash was brilliantly constructed from a mining car in the same, rural town (repurposed antiquities aside, this cookery turned out sleek and modern as hell). If you're looking for a charmer of a home on a charmer of a street, then this is your 'hood...and this is definitely your house. Remarks: For those of you jonesing to be our neighbors (really, this should be all of you), we've got a wee bit of fantastic news. This stellar spot has just cropped up but a mere stone's throw from our South Temple HQ, and we're thrilled to death to be repping such a beautiful space on such a near-and-dear street (really, it's the best). When it comes to this particular salty slice, we'll start from the curb, 'cause she's got appeal in spades. This craftsman-style casa in sporting a pretty impressive bay window that looks out onto a beautifully-landscaped front yard (think: people-watching over Parcheesi in the fall, street-side snowmen come winter). Inside, you'll find a spacious and well-kept interior that bears phenomenal natural light year round. Outfitted with some vintage-inspired touches (specifically those delish French doors to the formal dining room, the stained glass peppered throughout, and the full walk-in pantry), this betty has just enough updates to make the lives lived within nice 'n' easy. Newer appliances, some slick hardwood floors, and a finished basement (translation: the rough stuff is taken care of, and all that's left to do is settle in and make the space yours). Out back you'll find a sensationally private patio (the previous owners considered putting in pool–we wholeheartedly second that notion), as well as a few off-street, covered parking spots–they'll be fab come cooler temps). Call us biased, but we happen to think this is one of the greatest streets in the ol' US of A. Won't you be our neighbor? Remarks: This two-story Colonial Revival styled residence is located in the prestigious Federal Heights neighborhood. Step through the curved portico to the grand entry where curved archways lead to the formal entertaining rooms. The formal living room has a fireplace and two sets of arch top French doors that lead to the den. The formal dining room is beautifully decorated, has ample seating room, and access to the covered patio through French doors. The gourmet kitchen has top-of-the-line appliances such as a six burner gas Wolf cooktop, double ovens, wine refrigerator, and a Bosch dishwasher. The kitchen features granite counter tops, a center island, and a separate bar area. A cozy family room and powder room are tucked away near the dining room and kitchen.  The classic curved staircase takes you upstairs where you will find an executive office, two bedrooms, a full bath, and the master retreat. The spacious master suite includes a sitting area and a master bath with soaking tub and double vanity. The lower level has an additional three bedrooms, bath, laundry room, and a recreation room. The professionally landscaped grounds include a covered patio, large brick entertaining patio, and grassy areas surrounded by perennials and mature trees.  Conveniently located near the University of Utah, downtown Salt Lake, and nearby mountain trails.

Remarks: As you drive through the charming, tree-lined signature streets of Federal Heights, you get a sense of the prominence and history that define this premier Salt Lake neighborhood. Completely renovated and updated in 2004 by the owner-architect, the home delivers oversized rooms and contemporary features within the architectural style of the period. Artfully designed, the timeless materials and the meticulous craftsmanship is extraordinary and unique. The outstanding attention to detail is evident throughout. An artist's studio (or future guest house) was built on the .70 acre property at the time of renovation with a linear lap pool built in between. Framed by mature trees and a beautifully designed gardens and landscape, the view from every set of French doors (all five of them) presents a balanced, serene picture and invites the outdoors in. The floor plan is well designed and functional with a modern feeling. The living room opens into a family room with custom cabinetry and wet bar – ideal for entertaining. The professionally designed kitchen offers a sophisticated entertaining venue as well as a cozy dining area with a fireplace. A well-appointed formal dining room sits between the two and if the walls could talk, they would tell stories of spectacular dinner parties, celebrations and memorable events. The large master bedroom is a tranquil and sophisticated retreat. Two more bedrooms (one being used as a den currently) are on the same level as well as an additional full bath and laundry. Downstairs, there is an exercise room, large laundry/craft room, workshop, storage and flexible space. The artist's studio is fully equipped with a kitchen, bath and laundry. There is garage space for three cars plus exceptional storage. State of the art plumbing, electrical and smart system technology and integrated speakers and museum quality lighting are found throughout this prestigious residence. The lifestyle is classic Salt Lake City with skiing, tennis, biking, hiking, golf, country clubs and the many outdoor activities this area is known for, within a short drive away. Remarks: The goal was to restore this prairie style bungalow such that it would evoke that era's purity of craftsmanship. Painted wood work was stripped and restored on the original cabinetry, hardware and fixtures were chosen for authenticity, and in the downstairs bunk and bathroom additions touches like subway and hex tile were used to seamlessly integrate with the original structure. Throughout, there is a fluidity between these era specific finishes and the incorporation of modern conveniences like central air, contemporary appliances, and a two car garage. While the photos will capture this aesthetic, touring the property in person reveals depth in these details.  The property's immediate setting is a treelined street nestled at the edge of the Marmalade District, with restaurants and shops just around the corner. Geographically, you have the broader convenience of a location less than ten minutes from Salt Lake's International airport, six blocks from downtown shopping, and an appropriate four blocks to freeway access.

Remarks: SLC–our fabulous city of salt, our home, our love, our muse–was founded July 24th, 1847 (Pioneer Day!). Soon thereafter, in 1878, this resplendently-historic homestead was built. Tucked into the be-fruited streets of Marmalade, this majestic casa is beautiful, private, and most certainly a taste of the "good ol' days". Though the bones be old, make no mistake–this is a sturdy build. There are plenty of original, historic details throughout the space, and all of the new work/upgrades have been completed using period-appropriate materials and design (including an amaze O'Keefe Merritt range in the kitchen, and sublime vintage tiles in the bathroom). High ceilings, large, natural-light-givin' windows, and six (6!) original fireplaces make this spot equal parts "venerable vintage" and "breezy retreat". Originally built as a three-room structure, it was expanded in Eastlake style to include a formal dining room, butler's pantry (fancy), kitchen, and an additional three bedrooms and two bathrooms. Also included: two laundry rooms (one up, one down) and a steam shower in the upstairs bath. The downstairs bathroom is plumbed and wired, ready to install whichever ornate, clawfooted tub you choose, and the owners have historically-accurate floor tile ready and waiting to be laid down and made rad (also ready for your touches: professionally-drawn design plans for sink and full shower). The backyard is a lush, fruitful, and utterly private paradise (think: The Secret Garden). The large rock wall keeps hidden a new custom-build shed, a few mature trees (including pear, peach, cherry, apple, and plum for goods long into the fall), a couple of raised veggie garden beds (with automated full watering system), and a cute as all get-out two-story stone playhouse. The possibilities are endless with this sweet old space. For lovers of SLC's past, present, and bright future: this is the place.  Plumbed, but unfinished bathroom in basement. Remarks: Mountain style residence with a contemporary flair situated on a quiet cul-de-sac in Arlington Hills. This SLC neighborhood is located on the north bench of SLC between the Downtown and the University of Utah, abutting the mountains. The nucleus of the home is the Great Room which has vaulted ceilings, a wall of windows with panoramic views of the SLC valley, and Qquirrh and Wasatch Mountain ranges. The Great Room opens to the large dining area that has 2 sets of French doors that lead to the outdoor Trex's deck with the stacked stone gas fireplace and hot tub. The gourmet kitchen has natural cherry wood cabinets, granite countertops and slate flooring. It is well-equipped with stainless steel double ovens, 2-Sub-Zero refrigerated drawers and Sub-Zero refrigerator, 4 burner Wolf gas range with griddle and hooded vent, prep sink, wine cooler and 2 new dishwashers. The well-lite executive office has a gas fireplace and dramatic views. Main level master suite has direct access to a sun deck with views of the valley and there is a large walk-in closet with additional space to add a second walk-in closet, nursery or study.  The master bath has two vessels sinks, soaking tub and separate shower. The lower level has a daylight basement with a family room, billiard area, craft room and additional sleeping quarters. Plus an extra deep 3 car garage.
